# Exploration Approach

Use charter-based exploratory testing.

Each session must have a clear mission.

Do not wander randomly.

Timebox each charter to approximately 15–30 minutes unless the user requests a different duration.

A good charter has this format:

```text
Explore [feature or area] with focus on [risk or concern].
Attack [input or workflow] looking for [failure class].
Tour [feature] as [persona] and note [quality concern].
```

Examples:

- Explore the registration flow with focus on error handling.
- Attack all input fields looking for validation and injection failures.
- Tour checkout as a guest user and note friction points.
- Explore file upload with focus on large files and unsupported types.
- Explore pagination and sorting with focus on state persistence.
- Attack permission boundaries by switching roles and direct URLs.

---

# Charter Design Rules

For every feature, generate charters covering at least:

1. Core user flow
2. Input validation
3. Navigation and state handling
4. Error handling and recovery
5. Permissions and session behavior
6. Data persistence
7. Integration failure
8. Accessibility and responsive behavior

For CRUD features, include charters for:

- Create
- Read/Search
- Update
- Delete
- Restore or undo, if applicable
- Audit trail, if applicable
- Pagination, sorting, and filtering
- Concurrent updates

For search/list features, include charters for:

- empty results
- partial match
- exact match
- multiple filters
- clearing filters
- pagination persistence
- sorting after filtering
- export, if available
- stale data after edit/delete

For form-heavy features, include charters for:

- required fields
- optional fields
- field dependencies
- numeric boundaries
- date boundaries
- special characters
- duplicate submission
- save draft, if available
- unsaved changes warning

---

# The 8 Testing Tours

Use these tours to guide exploration.

## 1. The Unhappy Path Tour

Intentionally do things wrong.

Probe:

- Click buttons multiple times rapidly.
- Submit empty forms.
- Submit partially completed forms.
- Navigate backward mid-flow.
- Refresh during form entry.
- Refresh during save.
- Open the same record in two tabs.
- Copy and paste the URL into a private window.
- Attempt actions after session expiration.
- Submit after signing out from another tab.

Look for:

- duplicate records
- missing validation
- stale state
- broken redirects
- unhandled errors
- data loss

---

## 2. The Landmark Tour

Visit every visible and hidden navigation point.

Probe:

- every menu item
- every submenu
- every link
- every footer link
- every help link
- every icon button
- every modal trigger
- every dropdown action
- every breadcrumb
- keyboard shortcuts mentioned in docs

Look for:

- broken links
- incorrect permissions
- inconsistent labels
- missing active state
- wrong breadcrumbs
- dead-end pages

---

## 3. The Garbage Collector Tour

Put bad data everywhere.

Probe:

- 10,000 characters in text fields
- empty strings
- whitespace-only values
- newlines
- tabs
- emoji
- Unicode
- RTL text
- Japanese/Chinese/Korean characters
- HTML tags such as `<b>bold</b>`
- XSS payloads such as `<script>alert(1)</script>`
- SQL injection patterns such as `' OR 1=1--`
- numbers in text fields
- text in number fields
- negative numbers
- decimals where integers are expected
- huge numbers
- past dates where future dates are expected
- future dates where past dates are expected

Look for:

- accepted invalid data
- broken layouts
- encoding issues
- stored XSS
- server errors
- inconsistent client/server validation

---

## 4. The Saboteur Tour

Simulate real-world failures.

Probe:

- slow network
- offline mode
- API timeout
- server error response
- third-party service unavailable
- long operation interrupted by navigation
- browser closed during upload/save
- session timeout after long idle period
- sign out in another tab, then submit from current tab
- stale CSRF token
- retry after failure

Look for:

- missing loading states
- endless spinners
- duplicate submission on retry
- partial saves
- data corruption
- unclear recovery path

---

## 5. The Supermodel Tour

Test as different personas.

Use these personas:

- first-time user
- returning user
- power user
- admin user
- restricted user
- unauthenticated user
- mobile user
- keyboard-only user
- screen-reader user
- slow-connection user

Probe:

- different role permissions
- unusual order of operations
- keyboard navigation
- small viewport behavior
- high zoom
- touch target usability
- low bandwidth behavior

Look for:

- permission leaks
- inaccessible controls
- confusing UX
- hidden required actions
- mobile layout failures

---

## 6. The Obsessive Tourist Tour

Repeat actions many times.

Probe:

- submit the same form repeatedly
- click Save rapidly
- create multiple records in sequence
- upload the same file repeatedly
- delete and recreate records
- generate enough records to trigger pagination
- perform the same search many times
- switch filters repeatedly

Look for:

- duplicate records
- performance degradation
- pagination bugs
- memory leaks
- stale caches
- inconsistent counters
- rate-limit issues

---

## 7. The Anti-Tourist Tour

Ignore the intended UI path and test adjacent behaviors.

Probe:

- manipulate query parameters
- access detail pages directly by URL
- change IDs in the URL
- inspect network payloads
- compare UI validation with API validation
- modify local storage/session storage where applicable
- test API response assumptions
- check cookies and token storage
- test browser autocomplete behavior

Look for:

- IDOR
- authorization bypass
- sensitive data exposure
- client-only validation
- unsafe local storage
- missing server-side validation

---

## 8. The Accessibility Tour

Probe accessibility intentionally.

Check:

- logical tab order
- all controls reachable by keyboard
- visible focus indicator
- form labels, not placeholder-only labels
- error messages announced to assistive technology
- meaningful alt text
- modal focus trapping
- Escape key behavior for modals
- 200% zoom support
- small viewport support
- touch targets at least 44x44px
- color is not the only indicator
- sufficient contrast for text and status indicators

Look for:

- keyboard traps
- skipped controls
- inaccessible validation errors
- visual-only feedback
- overlapping content
- clipped text

---

# Bug Intuition Checklist

During every exploratory session, check:

```text
□ Page title updates correctly after navigation.
□ Loading states appear during async operations.
□ Empty states are useful and accurate.
□ Error messages appear for all failure scenarios.
□ Success feedback appears after user actions.
□ Forms do not submit unexpectedly on Enter.
□ Save buttons prevent duplicate submission.
□ Required fields are clearly indicated.
□ Client and server validation are consistent.
□ Browser back and refresh do not corrupt state.
□ Direct URL access respects permissions.
□ Deleted records cannot be accessed unexpectedly.
□ Pagination remains correct after create/edit/delete.
□ Sorting remains correct after filtering.
□ Search results reset predictably when filters are cleared.
□ Passwords are not visible in URLs or network requests.
□ PII is not logged in the browser console.
□ Tokens are not stored unsafely in localStorage.
□ HTTPS is enforced with no mixed content warnings.
□ Sensitive data is not present in page source comments.
□ Clipboard, camera, and microphone permissions are not requested without reason.
□ Print view is reasonable when relevant.
□ Copy/paste preserves meaningful text.
□ Audit logs are created for critical changes when required.
□ Timezone-sensitive dates display consistently.
```

